            <physdesc>
              <genreform>AMsS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Poem written for Cousin Grace.]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
      </c01>
      <c01 level="series" id="d1e214">
        <did>
          <unittitle>Letters</unittitle>
        </did>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e218">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>Byron Johnson Rees</persname></unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1917 Apr 27</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>TLS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Thanks him for reading the essay and calls
                  attention to a misprint; invites him to come to 
                  <geogname>New York</geogname>to see 
                  <corpname>Columbia University</corpname>. ]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e246">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>Leo Leonard Twinem</persname></unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1921 Nov 21</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>ALS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[States that his play, 
                  <bibref xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" xlink:href=""><title xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="">Hearts Enduring</title></bibref>, is published by 
                  <corpname>Duffield &amp; Co.</corpname>, and Duffield
                  is also his business representative; can make royalty
                  arrangements if given more information.]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e277">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>Katherine Lee Bates</persname></unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1922 Mar 26</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>ALS,</genreform>
              <extent>2 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Sends copy of later volume of his poems than the
                  one she used for his introduction; thanks for the
                  delightful visit to 
                  <corpname>Wellesley</corpname>and to Mrs. Ward for
                  her hospitality; greetings to 
                  <persname>Sophie Chantal Hart</persname>and 
                  <persname>Vida Dutton Scudder</persname>. ]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e308">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>William Griffith</persname>,
                  Esq.</unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1932 Oct 28</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>TLS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Cannot preside as toastmaster at the anniversary
                  dinner (50th anniversary of the 
                  <corpname>Author's Club</corpname>) since the date
                  was changed from Nov 10 to Nov 9 because he is giving
                  a lecture at 
                  <corpname>Columbia University</corpname>that
                  day.]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e337">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>William Griffith</persname></unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1932 Nov 2</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>TLS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[ 
                  <persname>James Howard Bridge</persname>visited him
                  about suggestions for toastmastership of the 
                  <corpname>Author's Club</corpname>anniversary dinner
                  but he will not be able to attend the dinner]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e365">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>John Stuart Groves</persname></unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1940 Feb 19</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>TPCS</genreform>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Consents to autograph his book, 
                  <bibref xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" xlink:href=""><title xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="">The Moral Obligation</title></bibref>. ]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e390">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to 
                  <persname>John Stuart Groves</persname></unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1940 Feb 24</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>TLS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Returns 
                  <bibref xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" xlink:href=""><title xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="">The Moral Obligation</title></bibref>with annotation and autograph; considers
                  this his first book and dates his reputation from it,
                  even though it is listed as tenth in 
                  <bibref xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="">Who's Who</bibref>, "since it is the first
                  book in which I expressed myself."]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
        <c02 level="item" id="d1e421">
          <did>
            <unittitle><persname>John Erskine</persname>to Gay</unittitle>
            <unitdate era="ce" calendar="gregorian">1941 Dec 16</unitdate>
            <physdesc>
              <genreform>TLS,</genreform>
              <extent>1 p.</extent>
            </physdesc>
          </did>
          <scopecontent>
            <p>[Expresses gratitude for kindness during visit;
                  was pleased to see Mrs. Beaman; is proud that 
                  <persname>(Henry) Lee Shippey</persname>mentioned him
                  in his column.]</p>
          </scopecontent>
        </c02>
      </c01>
